Installing the GitHub CLI (gh) on Arch Linux is straightforward because it’s available in the official repositories. You don't even need to mess with the AUR unless you want the bleeding-edge development version.

Here is the quickest way to get it up and running.

1. Installation
Open your terminal and use pacman to install the package:

Bash
sudo pacman -S github-cli
2. Authentication
Once installed, you need to link the CLI to your GitHub account. Run the following command and follow the interactive prompts:

Bash
gh auth login
What to expect during login:

Account: GitHub.com (or GitHub Enterprise).

Protocol: HTTPS or SSH (SSH is generally preferred for seamless pushing/pulling).

Method: "Login with a web browser" is the easiest. It will give you an 8-character code to paste into a browser window.

3. Verification
To make sure everything is linked correctly, check your status:

Bash
gh auth status
Common Commands to Get Started
Now that you're authenticated, here are the most useful "day one" commands:

Command	Action
gh repo clone user/repo	Clones a repository locally.
gh repo create	Starts a new repo on GitHub from your terminal.
gh pr list	Lists all open pull requests for the current repo.
gh issue create	Opens a new issue without leaving the CLI.
Pro Tip: If you use a lot of aliases or want to customize the CLI experience, you can find your configuration files at ~/.config/gh/.

